26 SUBCHAPTER 1
27 MAINE OFFICE OF COMMUNITY AFFAIRS
28 Sec. C-3. 5 MRSA c. 310-B, sub-c. 2 is enacted to read:
29 SUBCHAPTER 2
30 STATE RESILIENCE OFFICE
31 §3211. State Resilience Office
32 1. Establishment; duties; administration. The State Resilience Office is established
33 within the office. The State Resilience Office shall coordinate and assist implementation
34 of the State's resilience policies and activities designed to improve resistance to extreme
35 weather events; collaborate with state agencies, county, municipal and tribal governments,
36 regional councils and county, local and tribal emergency management agencies and other
37 stakeholders to harmonize policy objectives and implementation of resilience policies and
Page 4 - 132LR0939(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 29, L.D. 1
318 activities designed to improve resistance to extreme weather events across all levels of
329 government; promote natural hazard risk management across all levels of government;
430 assist county, municipal and tribal governments in this State to manage risks from extreme
441 weather events and natural hazards, such as flooding and damaging winds, through
452 planning, technical assistance and financial support; and prioritize and coordinate projects
463 for federal funding.
7 2. Administration of certain programs. The State Resilience Office shall administer
8 the Community Resilience Partnership Program established in section 3109, the floodplain
9 management program established in Title 12, section 408 and the State Floodplain Mapping
10 Fund established in Title 12, section 409.
11 3. Report. Annually, beginning October 1, 2026, the State Resilience Office shall
12 report to the Bureau of Insurance within the Department of Professional and Financial
13 Regulation and the joint standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over
14 insurance matters on the uses, activities and outcomes supported by funds from the transfer
15 made pursuant to Title 24-A, section 606.
16 4. Rulemaking. The State Resilience Office may adopt rules as necessary for the
17 proper administration of this subchapter. Rules adopted pursuant to this subsection are
18 routine technical rules as defined in chapter 375, subchapter 2‑A.
19 §3212. State Resilience Fund
20 1. Fund established. The State Resilience Fund, referred to in this section as "the
21 fund," is established as a dedicated, nonlapsing fund administered by the office for the
22 purpose of providing funds for the mitigation of risk to communities, buildings and
23 infrastructure from extreme weather events and other natural hazards such as flooding and
24 damaging winds.
25 2. Sources of funding. The fund consists of any money received from the following
26 sources:
27 A. Contributions from private sources;
28 B. Federal funds and grant awards;
29 C. The proceeds of any bonds issued for the purposes for which the fund is established;
30 and
31 D. Any state or other funds received in support of the purposes for which the fund is
32 established.
33 3. Disbursements from fund. The office shall apply funds in the fund to support
34 data, planning tools, technical assistance and project funding designed to increase the
35 resilience of county, municipal and tribal governments, state and local infrastructure,
36 businesses and other state entities to risks from extreme weather events and natural hazards
37 such as flooding and damaging winds.
